Okay. Fine. You want to know how to… terminate a C program? It’s not exactly a glamorous topic.

The simplest way is to use the `exit()` function. It’s part of the standard C library.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  printf("This is a C program.\n");
  exit(0); // Exit with a status code of 0 (success)
  printf("This line will not be executed.\n"); // This line is unreachable
  return 0;
}
```

The `exit()` function immediately terminates the program and returns a status code to the operating system. A status code of 0 typically indicates successful execution.

Alternatively, you can use the `return` statement within the `main()` function. If `main()` returns a non-zero value, the program will also terminate.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  printf("This is a C program.\n");
  return 1; // Exit with a status code of 1 (failure)
  printf("This line will not be executed.\n"); // This line is unreachable
  return 0;
}
```

However, `exit()` is generally preferred because it handles cleanup tasks more reliably, such as closing files and freeing memory.

Finally, if you encounter a fatal error (like a segmentation fault), the program will usually terminate abruptly. You can't reliably control this type of termination.

